# Guide: How to Install VS Code, Open Our GitHub Repository Locally, and Push Changes

This guide explains how to set up Visual Studio Code, clone our repository to your computer, open it locally, make changes, push them to GitHub, and create a pull request.

Our repository is:

`https://github.com/CMPE252/customer-churn-prediction`

---

## 1. If Visual Studio Code is not installed on your computer, do this: install VS Code

Go to the official Visual Studio Code website and download the version for your operating system:

* Windows
* macOS
* Linux

Install it like a normal application.

After installation:

* Open VS Code once
* Make sure it launches correctly

VS Code is the program you will use to open the project folder, edit files, and use the built-in terminal.

---

## 2. If Git is not installed on your computer, do this: install Git

Git is required to clone the repository, create branches, commit changes, and push to GitHub.

### On Windows

Download and install Git for Windows.

During installation:

* If you are unsure, keeping the default options is usually fine

### On macOS

Open the Terminal app and type:

```bash
git --version
```

If Git is not installed, macOS may prompt you to install developer tools. Accept that prompt.

### On Linux

Install Git using your package manager.

For Ubuntu/Debian:

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install git
```

After installation, check that Git works:

```bash
git --version
```

If you see a version number, Git is installed correctly.

---

## 3. If you have not used the terminal much before, do this: learn the only part you need here

You do not need advanced terminal knowledge for this workflow. You only need to know how to:

* open the terminal
* copy and paste commands
* press Enter to run them

### On Windows

You can use:

* Command Prompt
* PowerShell
* Git Bash

Git Bash is usually the easiest option if you installed Git for Windows.

### On macOS

Use the **Terminal** app.

### On Linux

Use your default **Terminal** app.

When this guide tells you to run a command, it means:

1. Open the terminal
2. Paste the command
3. Press Enter

---

## 4. If this is your first time setting up Git on this computer, do this: set your name and email

Git uses this information to label your commits.

Open a terminal and run:

```bash
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your_email@example.com"
```

Example:

```bash
git config --global user.name "Jane Doe"
git config --global user.email "janedoe@gmail.com"
```

To check that it worked, run:

```bash
git config --global --list
```

You should see your name and email in the output.

It is best to use the same email address you use for GitHub.

---

## 5. If you are not sure whether you should clone directly or fork first, do this: decide based on your access

There are two possible workflows.

### Option A: You are a collaborator on the repository

Use this if you have permission to push branches directly to the repository.

You can:

* clone the repository directly
* create a new branch
* push your branch
* open a pull request

### Option B: You are not a collaborator on the repository

Use this if you do not have permission to push to the original repository.

You must:

* fork the repository to your own GitHub account
* clone your fork
* push to your fork
* open a pull request from your fork to the original repository

If you are unsure, the easiest way to tell is this:

* if pushing directly fails because of permissions, use the fork workflow

---

# Workflow A: If you are a collaborator, follow these steps

## 6. If you have collaborator access, do this: clone the repository to your computer

Choose where you want the project folder to live on your computer first.

For example:

* Desktop
* Documents
* a Projects folder

Open your terminal and move to that location.

### Example: move to Desktop

#### Windows Git Bash

```bash
cd ~/Desktop
```

#### macOS/Linux

```bash
cd ~/Desktop
```

Now clone the repository:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/CMPE252/customer-churn-prediction.git
```

This downloads the repository to your computer.

After cloning, enter the project folder:

```bash
cd customer-churn-prediction
```

To verify you are inside the project folder, run:

```bash
pwd
```

And list the files:

```bash
ls
```

You should see the project contents.

---

## 7. If you want to open the repository in VS Code, do this: open the folder

While still inside the project folder in the terminal, run:

```bash
code .
```

This opens the current folder in VS Code.

### If `code .` does not work

That usually means the VS Code command-line shortcut is not enabled.

In that case:

1. Open VS Code manually
2. Click **File > Open Folder**
3. Select the `customer-churn-prediction` folder

Now the project is open in VS Code.

---

## 8. If you have opened the repository in VS Code, do this: locate the main areas of the interface

Inside VS Code:

* The **left sidebar** shows files and folders
* The **main area** opens files for editing
* The **Terminal** can be opened from the top menu:

  * **Terminal > New Terminal**

Open the built-in terminal in VS Code now.

That terminal will usually start inside your project folder.

---

## 9. If you want to confirm Git recognizes the repository correctly, do this: run status

In the VS Code terminal, run:

```bash
git status
```

If everything is set up correctly, Git will say you are on a branch and the working tree is clean.

---

## 10. If you are about to start working on a task, do this: create your own branch

Do not work directly on `main` unless your team specifically wants that workflow.

Create a new branch:

```bash
git checkout -b your-branch-name
```

Example:

```bash
git checkout -b fix-readme-jade
```

This creates a new branch and switches to it.

To verify your branch, run:

```bash
git branch
```

The current branch will have a `*` next to it.

---

## 11. If you want to make changes, do this: edit files in VS Code

Now edit the files you need.

Examples:

* update `README.md`
* edit a notebook
* modify files inside the project folders

Save your changes after editing:

* Windows/Linux: `Ctrl + S`
* macOS: `Cmd + S`

---

## 12. If you finished editing and want to see what changed, do this: check Git status

Run:

```bash
git status
```

Git will show which files were changed.

---

## 13. If you are ready to include your changes in a commit, do this: stage the files

To stage all changed files:

```bash
git add .
```

If you only want to stage one specific file:

```bash
git add filename
```

Example:

```bash
git add README.md
```

Then check again:

```bash
git status
```

Files that are staged will appear under something like “Changes to be committed”.

---

## 14. If your changes are staged and you want to save them in project history, do this: commit

Commit your changes with a message:

```bash
git commit -m "Write a clear description of what you changed"
```

Example:

```bash
git commit -m "Update README instructions for dataset usage"
```

A commit saves a checkpoint in the project history.

---

## 15. If you want your branch to appear on GitHub, do this: push your branch

Run:

```bash
git push -u origin your-branch-name
```

Example:

```bash
git push -u origin fix-readme-jade
```

The `-u` option helps Git remember the connection between your local branch and the remote branch.

If Git asks you to sign in:

* follow the login instructions
* on some systems, a browser window will open
* complete the authentication steps

---

## 16. If your branch is pushed and you want your team to review your work, do this: open a pull request

Go to the repository on GitHub.

GitHub often shows a button like:

* **Compare & pull request**

Click it.

Then:

1. Make sure the base repository is the original repo
2. Make sure the base branch is usually `main`
3. Make sure the compare branch is your branch
4. Add a title
5. Add a short description of what you changed
6. Click **Create pull request**

Done.

---

# Workflow B: If you are not a collaborator, follow these steps

## 17. If you do not have direct push access, do this first: fork the repository

Go to:

`https://github.com/CMPE252/customer-churn-prediction`

Click the **Fork** button on GitHub.

This creates your own copy of the repository under your GitHub account.

After forking, your fork will look like:

```text
https://github.com/YOUR-USERNAME/customer-churn-prediction
```

---

## 18. If you created a fork, do this: clone your fork instead of the original repository

Open the terminal and move to the folder where you want the project.

Then run:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/YOUR-USERNAME/customer-churn-prediction.git
```

Enter the folder:

```bash
cd customer-churn-prediction
```

Open it in VS Code:

```bash
code .
```

If that does not work, open the folder manually in VS Code.

---

## 19. If you forked the repository, do this: connect the original repository as `upstream`

This lets you pull the latest changes from the original repository later.

Run:

```bash
git remote add upstream https://github.com/CMPE252/customer-churn-prediction.git
```

Now verify your remotes:

```bash
git remote -v
```

You should see:

* `origin` pointing to your fork
* `upstream` pointing to the original repository

---

## 20. If you are starting work in your fork, do this: create a branch

Run:

```bash
git checkout -b your-branch-name
```

Example:

```bash
git checkout -b add-notebook-notes
```

---

## 21. If you made changes in your fork, do this: stage and commit them

Stage all changes:

```bash
git add .
```

Commit them:

```bash
git commit -m "Describe your changes clearly"
```

Example:

```bash
git commit -m "Clean notebook comments and improve documentation"
```

---

## 22. If you want your changes on GitHub, do this: push to your fork

Run:

```bash
git push -u origin your-branch-name
```

Example:

```bash
git push -u origin add-notebook-notes
```

This pushes the branch to your fork, not the original repository.

---

## 23. If your branch is on your fork and you want the original repository to review it, do this: open a pull request

Go to your fork on GitHub.

GitHub will usually show a **Compare & pull request** button.

Click it.

Then make sure:

* the **base repository** is `CMPE252/customer-churn-prediction`
* the **base branch** is `main`
* the **head repository** is your fork
* the **compare branch** is your branch

Add a title and description, then create the pull request.

---

# Keeping your local repository up to date

## 24. If you already cloned the project before and want the latest changes from GitHub, do this: pull the latest version

### If you cloned the original repository directly

Switch to `main`:

```bash
git checkout main
```

Pull the latest changes:

```bash
git pull origin main
```

### If you are using a fork

First get the latest changes from the original repository:

```bash
git checkout main
git pull upstream main
```

Then push those updates to your fork if needed:

```bash
git push origin main
```

This keeps your fork synchronized.

---

# Recommended workflow each time you work

## 25. If you are starting a new task later, do this in order

1. Open VS Code
2. Open the project folder
3. Open the terminal in VS Code
4. Go to `main`

```bash
git checkout main
```

5. Pull the latest changes

For direct clone:

```bash
git pull origin main
```

For fork workflow:

```bash
git pull upstream main
```

6. Create a new branch

```bash
git checkout -b new-branch-name
```

7. Make changes
8. Save files
9. Check status

```bash
git status
```

10. Stage changes

```bash
git add .
```

11. Commit

```bash
git commit -m "Your commit message"
```

12. Push

```bash
git push -u origin new-branch-name
```

13. Open a pull request on GitHub

